==English==

===Etymology===
First attested [[w:1393|1393]], from {{etyl|la}} ''[[simile#Latin|simile]]'' ("comparison, likeness", "parallel"), originally from ''[[simile#Latin|simile]]'' the neuter form of ''[[similis]]'' ("like, similar, resembling"). Confer the English ''[[similar]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-simile.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|linguistics}} A [[figure of speech]] in which one thing is compared to another, generally using ''like'' or ''as''.
#:* ''“A woman needs a man like a fish needs a bicycle”'' &mdash; [[w:Irina Dunn|Irina Dunn]], [[w:1970|1970]]
#: ''A '''simile''' is like a metaphor.'' <!-- I almost deleted this but thought Wiktionary can afford a little fun. -->

